meaningful. And Danette's talk was really beautiful in terms of thinking about some

509
00:29:58.780 --> 00:30:01.240
of the kinetic parameters of how you would optimize a degrader.

510
00:30:01.640 --> 00:30:04.600
But if you think about in terms of how you're going to control the pathway,

511
00:30:04.960 --> 00:30:08.479
inhibition is intended to be a complete

512
00:30:08.520 --> 00:30:11.760
blockade of a protein's function, enzymatic protein function.

513
00:30:12.180 --> 00:30:16.040
But if you really understand your ability to maintain

514
00:30:16.100 --> 00:30:20.080
drug levels throughout the course of treatment in the wild,

515
00:30:20.090 --> 00:30:23.960
even in a patient population, your ability to have enough inhibitor on board

516
00:30:23.969 --> 00:30:27.480
to always control every bit of your enzymatic function of a protein

517
00:30:27.940 --> 00:30:31.700
is pretty much unachievable. And the difference then in terms of

518
00:30:31.880 --> 00:30:35.610
using an agent like a degrader that actually removes that protein and

519
00:30:35.680 --> 00:30:39.520
removes it to a point where there really isn't any protein left to expend

520
00:30:39.600 --> 00:30:43.380
its enzymatic function, it really gives you that very

521
00:30:43.460 --> 00:30:45.259
big differential of what would happen

522
00:30:46.240 --> 00:30:50.140
in the course of trying to pass a signal from the cell surface down

523
00:30:50.200 --> 00:30:50.420
to

524
00:30:51.240 --> 00:30:52.820
the nucleus of the cell.

525
00:30:54.399 --> 00:30:58.190
So one of the other learnings that we obtained in developing our

526
00:30:58.260 --> 00:31:01.980
degrader and truly trying to understand how it differentiate from inhibitors is

527
00:31:02.080 --> 00:31:06.060
that we actually observed that the degrader could cover the

528
00:31:06.180 --> 00:31:09.860
spans of mutation, whether or not we designed against them or not,

529
00:31:10.800 --> 00:31:14.580
in a superior way to inhibitors. And that was a surprise to us, and I think the

530
00:31:14.600 --> 00:31:18.140
field is still trying to internalize what is going to be the resistance

531
00:31:18.220 --> 00:31:21.420
mechanism of degraders. Certainly, there will be a resistance mechanism of

532
00:31:21.460 --> 00:31:25.290
degraders. But one of the very first, very dramatic learnings that

533
00:31:25.360 --> 00:31:29.200
we obtained is that we had very robust activity against

534
00:31:29.300 --> 00:31:32.930
all of the clinical mutations. I'm showing them here at the bottom of this

535
00:31:32.960 --> 00:31:36.770
plot. Whereas the inhibitors all designed to be very effective against one or

536
00:31:36.800 --> 00:31:37.480
two of these

537
00:31:38.620 --> 00:31:42.480
resistance mutations, always had liabilities and often two or three liabilities.

538
00:31:42.900 --> 00:31:46.720
And so this difference is really all about that induced

539
00:31:46.780 --> 00:31:50.300
proximity event, the transience that you have to

540
00:31:50.360 --> 00:31:52.550
obtain by bringing your ligase to your

541
00:31:53.540 --> 00:31:57.500
target of interest, and that the brief duration of that response

542
00:31:57.560 --> 00:32:01.060
allows you to accommodate a lot of affinities to your target of interest.

543
00:32:01.410 --> 00:32:05.400
Therefore, if they change due to mutation, you can still affect a brief

544
00:32:05.460 --> 00:32:07.800
ternary complex and still affect removal of the protein.

545
00:32:07.820 --> 00:32:11.000
And so this is a fundamental learning of this field that I think is really

546
00:32:11.280 --> 00:32:13.180
important for people to appreciate.

547
00:32:14.250 --> 00:32:17.420
The other piece that is important to think about when you think about, well, why

548
00:32:17.460 --> 00:32:21.240
does that work? We did use a binder that actually sat right in the active site

549
00:32:21.320 --> 00:32:25.040
pocket of BTK. And I'm showing you here our binder in blue, and I'm

550
00:32:25.100 --> 00:32:28.900
illustrating in red the amino acids that mutate in this

551
00:32:28.940 --> 00:32:32.840
pocket and yield a dead kinase. And in green,

552
00:32:32.920 --> 00:32:36.220
the amino acids that mutate and leave that kinase active.

553
00:32:36.260 --> 00:32:40.190
And so luckily in our design, and I think it was partly by design and

554
00:32:40.220 --> 00:32:43.660
partly by luck, we were able to choose a binder that really didn't interact with

555
00:32:43.700 --> 00:32:47.620
any of the side chains of these amino acids that would really distort the pocket

556
00:32:47.640 --> 00:32:50.220
and change the activity of this protein.

557
00:32:51.010 --> 00:32:54.840
So even if you choose a binder very adjacent to

558
00:32:55.340 --> 00:32:59.280
surfaces of the protein that could change through mutation in

559
00:32:59.300 --> 00:33:02.780
response to drug treatment, it doesn't preclude you from being able to create a

560
00:33:02.820 --> 00:33:05.000
degrader that still is very effective in that setting.

561
00:33:06.040 --> 00:33:09.920
One of the next learnings that we had, and this isn't a rate constant as Danette

562
00:33:09.940 --> 00:33:13.780
was really telling us about, but we really wanted to understand how much drug do

563
00:33:13.840 --> 00:33:17.600
we need in a cell or in a body to be able to affect this induced proximity.

564
00:33:18.040 --> 00:33:21.200
So the goal of making degraders is to be able to work

565
00:33:21.260 --> 00:33:25.060
substoichiometrically. What you're wanting to do is be able to have

566
00:33:25.100 --> 00:33:29.000
these transient interactions with proteins and not have to occupy

567
00:33:29.060 --> 00:33:33.040
your cell or your patient with more drug in molecule count than

568
00:33:33.080 --> 00:33:35.280
the proteins that that drug is trying to interact with.

569
00:33:35.760 --> 00:33:38.100
And so what I'm showing you here is the Cmax

570
00:33:39.320 --> 00:33:42.280
and the Cmin in free levels, and I'm comparing that.

571
00:33:42.400 --> 00:33:45.080
I'm using one of our effective clinical doses at 200 mgs

572
00:33:46.700 --> 00:33:50.580
QD, and I'm comparing that steady state rate to the amount of drug you would

573
00:33:50.640 --> 00:33:54.000
need to be effective with ibrutinib or zanubrutinib or even

574
00:33:54.040 --> 00:33:57.530
pirtobrutinib. And what you see is this very large difference,

575
00:33:57.640 --> 00:34:01.540
particularly to the non-covalent agents, of how much drug actually

576
00:34:01.760 --> 00:34:05.400
really needs to be dosed and maintained to be able to fully cover the

577
00:34:05.460 --> 00:34:08.040
activity of the target. And that

578
00:34:08.899 --> 00:34:12.660
amount of drug that is effective is really a translation of how

579
00:34:12.700 --> 00:34:16.640
efficient this drug is. So on the right, you see a different

580
00:34:16.700 --> 00:34:20.520
version, not exactly the rate calculation that Danette showed you, but

581
00:34:20.920 --> 00:34:24.700
it was a calculation derived to understand how many protein molecules

582
00:34:25.020 --> 00:34:28.460
in an hour you could degrade with any one molecule of degrader.

583
00:34:28.480 --> 00:34:32.281
And so in our dose range, our effective dose range, we're degrading about 10,000

584
00:34:32.301 --> 00:34:33.710
protein molecules per hour.

585
00:34:35.160 --> 00:34:37.080
So how does that translate into the dose we use?

586
00:34:37.140 --> 00:34:40.120
So this is a piece that kind of takes people a little bit to think about.

587
00:34:40.540 --> 00:34:41.301
Our approved

588
00:34:42.480 --> 00:34:46.290
dose to go forward into our registrational trials is 600 milligrams, and it seems

589
00:34:46.361 --> 00:34:49.200
actually a bit larger than you might expect if you're trying to dose

590
00:34:49.380 --> 00:34:53.011
substoichiometrically. But as most of us realize, most of these bifunctional

591
00:34:53.040 --> 00:34:55.801
molecules do not have the best bioavailability.

592
00:34:56.240 --> 00:34:59.000
And so you're usually fighting your formulation or your

593
00:34:59.500 --> 00:35:02.260
bioavailability to obtain a drug on board.

594
00:35:02.640 --> 00:35:06.440
But what I'm showing you here is a steady state PK profile of 600 milligrams, and

595
00:35:06.500 --> 00:35:07.860
you're seeing that it is below

596
00:35:08.980 --> 00:35:09.280
one

597
00:35:10.220 --> 00:35:14.060
nanomolar. And what that means is it's well below the 500 nanomolar that you need

598
00:35:14.100 --> 00:35:18.000
for pirto. It's still very low. But we're dosing at a level that we

599
00:35:18.040 --> 00:35:21.300
can go much above the wild type DC95 coverage.

600
00:35:21.340 --> 00:35:25.200
So we can dose to cover all of the different potencies that

601
00:35:25.240 --> 00:35:28.620
we've observed against the different mutations that are in our clinical population.

602
00:35:29.140 --> 00:35:32.980
And what does that mean? When we did our Project Optimist dose optimization,

603
00:35:33.040 --> 00:35:36.080
we compared between 200 milligrams and 600 milligrams

604
00:35:36.880 --> 00:35:40.460
in a randomized study, and we could clearly see the difference of progression-free

605
00:35:40.500 --> 00:35:44.120
survival when dosing at 600 because we really were obtaining a dose

606
00:35:44.480 --> 00:35:48.400
that would cover the full extent of the mutations that we were seeing in our very

607
00:35:48.460 --> 00:35:52.368
complex patient population.So does that higher dose,

608
00:35:52.488 --> 00:35:56.108
does it equate to less safety? So this is another extremely

609
00:35:56.148 --> 00:35:59.848
important parameter in this field, and there still is quite a bit of this

610
00:35:59.888 --> 00:36:03.688
understanding of how a degrader-induced proximity drugs might translate

611
00:36:03.748 --> 00:36:07.598
into safety. And I think it's even more relevant in the context of

612
00:36:07.608 --> 00:36:10.248
induced proximity, but we're talking about degraders here.

613
00:36:10.288 --> 00:36:13.028
So what I'm showing you here are the treatment

614
00:36:14.148 --> 00:36:17.078
emergent adverse events for either all doses on the

615
00:36:18.588 --> 00:36:21.067
left or at 600 milligrams on the right.

616
00:36:21.518 --> 00:36:24.548
And what you see actually is, if you look very closely,

617
00:36:25.468 --> 00:36:29.348
the profile of the 600 milligram dose is really no different than the profile

618
00:36:29.388 --> 00:36:32.388
of all of the doses together, meaning as you dose higher, you don't see a higher

619
00:36:32.468 --> 00:36:34.508
rate of adverse events.

620
00:36:36.208 --> 00:36:39.828
So if you look at it another way, if you look at the exposure response analysis, so

621
00:36:39.888 --> 00:36:43.508
this is a preliminary exposure response analysis, where we really have looked at

622
00:36:43.588 --> 00:36:47.208
all of the BK over the course of all of our patient dosing and

623
00:36:47.268 --> 00:36:51.208
related it to the probability of an event that is on

