00:38:42.868 --> 00:38:46.508
patients or in pre-clinical models, which we also did, we absolutely see

654
00:38:46.628 --> 00:38:46.868
no

655
00:38:49.868 --> 00:38:52.348
QT prolongation on treatment of the drug.

656
00:38:52.368 --> 00:38:54.288
And actually, the

657
00:38:55.628 --> 00:38:59.268
curve that I'm showing you here is a profile that is acceptable even to

658
00:38:59.468 --> 00:39:03.208
use outside of oncology. So quite

659
00:39:03.248 --> 00:39:06.848
distinct. So why is that? Why were we able to obtain this profile?

660
00:39:06.868 --> 00:39:09.048
Why are other degraders not always seeing this profile?

661
00:39:09.108 --> 00:39:12.748
Of course, there's myriad reasons. Every drug has their own parameters.

662
00:39:12.768 --> 00:39:14.658
But one of the reasons is selectivity.

663
00:39:15.268 --> 00:39:19.198
So we have spent quite a bit of time understanding the selectivity of

664
00:39:19.268 --> 00:39:22.948
all of our degraders. I think that's a fundamental piece of optimizing your

665
00:39:22.998 --> 00:39:26.448
degrader. And what's really freeing in the case of targeted protein degradation is

666
00:39:26.508 --> 00:39:29.928
you actually have a tool that can give you a broader view of selectivity than has

667
00:39:30.028 --> 00:39:33.848
been available for most other modalities, particularly inhibitors.

668
00:39:34.628 --> 00:39:38.368
Looking at the entirety of the proteome that you can sample in whatever cell type

669
00:39:38.408 --> 00:39:41.968
you look at is far more effective than looking at a kinome scan.

670
00:39:42.408 --> 00:39:45.428
So here I'm showing you the profile of vexbrotidig, and this is used at

