1237
01:13:34.512 --> 01:13:38.052
MET kinase, which comes along for the ride. Here's 1433.

1238
01:13:38.532 --> 01:13:42.132
This is the C-terminal site, and this is the N-terminal

1239
01:13:42.192 --> 01:13:46.092
phosphorylation site. Now you'll notice there's no density on

1240
01:13:46.212 --> 01:13:48.992
either side of that phosphorylation site.

1241
01:13:49.532 --> 01:13:53.312
So the protein is intrinsically disordered region of protein.

1242
01:13:53.752 --> 01:13:56.992
On either side of the 1433 site, it's intrinsically disordered.

1243
01:13:57.032 --> 01:13:59.332
We can't discern it in the cryo-EM map.

1244
01:14:00.112 --> 01:14:04.072
But at the site that's bound to 1433, it's highly structured.

1245
01:14:05.172 --> 01:14:08.252
So this gives us a general way of thinking about how to

1246
01:14:08.872 --> 01:14:12.122
modulate intrinsically disordered proteins by stabilizing their

1247
01:14:12.192 --> 01:14:15.472
protein-protein interactions, which are ordered and structured.

1248
01:14:17.632 --> 01:14:20.672
The other important point about this, because they're intrinsically disordered

1249
01:14:20.792 --> 01:14:24.452
structures, phosphopeptides, much easier to work with than

1250
01:14:24.492 --> 01:14:27.812
conditionally phosphorylated intrinsically disordered full-length proteins.

1251
01:14:28.212 --> 01:14:31.632
Phosphopeptides mimic the conformation, the shape, the

1252
01:14:31.672 --> 01:14:34.451
binding of the full-length protein.

1253
01:14:34.512 --> 01:14:38.312
So here you can see overlaps from the cryo-EM structure in dark blue

1254
01:14:38.632 --> 01:14:42.612
and a crystal structure in light blue of CRAF bound to 1433

1255
01:14:42.622 --> 01:14:43.072
in gray.

1256
01:14:43.912 --> 01:14:47.622
So we will use for biochemical assays, I may or may not say it crisply,

1257
01:14:48.152 --> 01:14:52.102
but for biochemical assays, we will be using the phosphopeptides, and then

1258
01:14:52.132 --> 01:14:53.762
in cells, we'll use full-length proteins.

1259
01:14:57.072 --> 01:15:00.772
So we're going to make a molecular glue that binds to that inhibitory site,

1260
01:15:01.212 --> 01:15:03.952
locks it down in the inhibited state, leaves the

1261
01:15:05.052 --> 01:15:07.452
constitutive site or the C-terminal site alone.

1262
01:15:09.112 --> 01:15:12.592
So the way we're going to do that is a technology called disulfide trapping or

1263
01:15:12.632 --> 01:15:16.162
disulfide tethering, and the basic concept is that we have

1264
01:15:17.052 --> 01:15:20.592
1433 in gray bound to CRAF in blue,

1265
01:15:21.052 --> 01:15:24.932
and one isoform of 1433, the sigma isoform, has a cysteine

1266
01:15:24.972 --> 01:15:28.642
residue positioned close to the end of that peptide, and that's

1267
01:15:28.692 --> 01:15:30.492
actually the fusococcin binding site.

1268
01:15:31.192 --> 01:15:35.042
So that gives us inspiration for how we might use covalency or reversible

1269
01:15:35.152 --> 01:15:38.612
covalency targeting that cysteine residue to bind to this new

1270
01:15:38.692 --> 01:15:41.992
composite surface formed by CRAF and 1433.

1271
01:15:42.952 --> 01:15:46.021
So we can do that experiment. We do a readout either by

1272
01:15:46.172 --> 01:15:48.922
fluorescence anisotropy or by mass spectrometry.

1273
01:15:49.392 --> 01:15:52.952
And in the mass spectrometry experiment, we do the experiment looking for

1274
01:15:52.972 --> 01:15:56.832
molecules that have disulfides that can bind to that cysteine

1275
01:15:56.892 --> 01:16:00.812
residue. We do that under conditions that allow us to distinguish chemical

1276
01:16:00.852 --> 01:16:03.592
reactivity from molecular recognition.

1277
01:16:04.152 --> 01:16:08.102
So in this experiment, we only identify molecules that bind to that binding site,

1278
01:16:08.592 --> 01:16:11.771
recognize that binding site, and also can make the disulfide bond.

1279
01:16:12.332 --> 01:16:14.892
So it's site-directed, but also measuring binding.

1280
01:16:15.412 --> 01:16:17.672
So we do the experiment this way with 1433.

1281
01:16:18.692 --> 01:16:22.572
Then we do it again in the presence of a phosphopeptide, and we look for

1282
01:16:22.612 --> 01:16:25.592
those molecules that bind preferentially in the presence of the

1283
01:16:25.612 --> 01:16:27.882
phosphopeptide over its absence.

1284
01:16:29.212 --> 01:16:33.202
So here's an example of the estrogen receptor and CRAF, just two examples

1285
01:16:33.732 --> 01:16:35.302
from many that are in this paper.

1286
01:16:37.012 --> 01:16:39.982
Here at the bottom, so you can see how different these two

1287
01:16:41.852 --> 01:16:45.662
structures are. So if you're a molecule looking at

1288
01:16:45.692 --> 01:16:49.432
that binding site, the estrogen receptor binding site looks very

1289
01:16:49.472 --> 01:16:53.422
different. The size, shape, what amino acids are pointing into that

1290
01:16:53.452 --> 01:16:55.722
pocket versus the CRAF site.

1291
01:16:56.832 --> 01:17:00.752
And in fact, we see most compounds are selective for one

1292
01:17:00.792 --> 01:17:04.672
or the other. So in these plots, each

1293
01:17:04.692 --> 01:17:08.592
compound is a dot. Along the x-axis, we have the amount that

1294
01:17:08.612 --> 01:17:11.172
they're bound in the absence of a phosphopeptide.

1295
01:17:11.632 --> 01:17:15.372
So this compound, for example, binds very well to 1433 but is

1296
01:17:15.382 --> 01:17:16.712
displaced by CRAF.

1297
01:17:17.612 --> 01:17:21.412
This is a neutral quadrant, and this is the potentially cooperative quadrant or

1298
01:17:21.452 --> 01:17:25.132
molecular glue quadrant, where this protein binds to the

1299
01:17:25.192 --> 01:17:29.022
compound well in the presence of CRAF, but very poorly in the absence of

1300
01:17:29.052 --> 01:17:32.732
CRAF. So we see a few different things in this cooperative

1301
01:17:32.772 --> 01:17:33.612
quadrant. Some

1302
01:17:34.432 --> 01:17:37.642
phosphopeptides pick up many more stabilizing hits than other

1303
01:17:37.652 --> 01:17:41.572
phosphopeptides. Some of these are common structures that show up

1304
01:17:41.612 --> 01:17:42.092
in

1305
01:17:43.592 --> 01:17:44.272
two or more

1306
01:17:45.352 --> 01:17:49.192
molecular glue screens, and others show up only

1307
01:17:49.252 --> 01:17:52.552
in one. So each target has specific and less

1308
01:17:52.652 --> 01:17:54.132
specific molecular glues.

1309
01:17:56.052 --> 01:17:59.652
So the way we characterize these, we can start with the mass spectrometry

1310
01:17:59.692 --> 01:18:03.592
experiment. As I mentioned, we want compounds that bind poorly to 1433 in

1311
01:18:03.632 --> 01:18:07.432
the absence of any peptide. Otherwise, they'll just get sopped up by all the

1312
01:18:07.512 --> 01:18:09.652
1433. It's a highly abundant protein.

1313
01:18:10.332 --> 01:18:14.132
Instead, we want those compounds to bind very strongly in the presence of the

1314
01:18:14.152 --> 01:18:17.712
phosphopeptide. So this gives us an apparent binding affinity.

1315
01:18:18.832 --> 01:18:22.632
We can then turn it around and say, well, what is the fluorescence polarization?

1316
01:18:22.712 --> 01:18:26.612
What is the degree of stabilization of the protein peptide

1317
01:18:26.652 --> 01:18:30.572
complex? And here the compound doesn't bind to the

1318
01:18:30.592 --> 01:18:34.512
peptide by itself. But when 1433 is present, as we titrate

1319
01:18:34.532 --> 01:18:38.352
in compound, we see an increase in anisotropy, indicating a

1320
01:18:38.432 --> 01:18:40.342
stabilization of that protein complex.

1321
01:18:41.192 --> 01:18:43.112
That gives us an EC50 for the molecule.

1322
01:18:43.852 --> 01:18:47.552
And then looking at doing the experiment yet another way, we can get the

1323
01:18:47.592 --> 01:18:51.272
apparent binding affinity for the protein-protein interaction.

1324
01:18:51.332 --> 01:18:54.972
Here it's about 10 micromolar in the absence of compound, and then

1325
01:18:54.982 --> 01:18:57.082
subnanomolar in the presence of compound.

1326
01:18:57.452 --> 01:19:00.032
So we can get very significant fold stabilization.

1327
01:19:01.612 --> 01:19:05.312
And I think for time I didn't include it, but using SPR, we can

1328
01:19:05.352 --> 01:19:09.312
get on rates and off rates and show that we're increasing the on rate by

1329
01:19:09.472 --> 01:19:12.972
10s to 30-fold, and we're decreasing the off rate by 30 to 100

1330
01:19:13.052 --> 01:19:16.864
fold.So the compound EC50s are in the low

1331
01:19:16.924 --> 01:19:20.804
micromolar range, but the effectiveness of those compounds at that

1332
01:19:20.844 --> 01:19:24.484
range is to stabilize the protein-protein interaction by 1,000-fold.

1333
01:19:24.984 --> 01:19:28.664
Okay, so with a small amount of compound, you can affect a very high

1334
01:19:28.744 --> 01:19:30.524
degree of protein complex formation.

1335
01:19:31.004 --> 01:19:33.284
Here's a crystal structure of what that compound looks like.

1336
01:19:33.704 --> 01:19:34.404
If I showed you the

1337
01:19:35.504 --> 01:19:39.424
CRAF peptide in a space filling model, you would hardly be able to see the compound

1338
01:19:39.444 --> 01:19:42.283
at all. Just a little bromine would stick up here.

1339
01:19:43.184 --> 01:19:46.724
So this compound is very intimately bound in this new protein

1340
01:19:47.064 --> 01:19:50.404
interaction site at the interface, like a piece of two-sided tape

1341
01:19:50.784 --> 01:19:53.584
contacting both the 1433 and the CRAF.

1342
01:19:54.784 --> 01:19:58.724
When you're really making good contacts with the partner protein, even though

1343
01:19:58.744 --> 01:20:02.304
1433 is common on all of these, you can see high selectivity.

1344
01:20:02.824 --> 01:20:06.704
This is an experiment using 80 different phosphopeptides with highly different

1345
01:20:07.164 --> 01:20:11.124
sequences and structures. And the dotted line, which you may or may not be

1346
01:20:11.144 --> 01:20:12.613
able to see, about here,

1347
01:20:13.504 --> 01:20:17.424
is the line for statistically significant stabilization at a high

1348
01:20:17.604 --> 01:20:21.444
concentration of compound. And really only one target

1349
01:20:21.484 --> 01:20:24.864
comes above that when we do dose responses that's significantly stabilized.

1350
01:20:24.904 --> 01:20:28.404
And we actually launched a new program around the APIN task because they're

1351
01:20:28.444 --> 01:20:29.544
excellent cancer targets.

1352
01:20:31.344 --> 01:20:35.244
So we have high selectivity when we target the composite surface on both

1353
01:20:35.344 --> 01:20:38.664
sides of the protein, both proteins at that composite surface.

1354
01:20:39.164 --> 01:20:42.084
So now what do we expect to see in cells? So here's that pathway again.

1355
01:20:42.744 --> 01:20:46.664
So if we stabilize this interaction, we would expect to see an increase in the

1356
01:20:46.684 --> 01:20:50.404
protein-protein interaction, which we do using a NanoBRET assay.

1357
01:20:51.304 --> 01:20:54.334
We would expect to see more of that phosphorylation sites.

1358
01:20:54.404 --> 01:20:57.703
We're inhibiting dephosphorylation by stabilizing that protein

1359
01:20:57.764 --> 01:21:00.024
complex. We can see that by western blot.

1360
01:21:01.484 --> 01:21:05.464
We would then expect to block downstream effects, such as interaction

1361
01:21:05.504 --> 01:21:09.104
with RAS. We also can block interaction with other RAF

1362
01:21:09.124 --> 01:21:12.344
kinases, and then blockade of the pathway by a

1363
01:21:12.684 --> 01:21:16.644
phospho-ERK inhibition. And in this assay, we inhibit the pathway about as

1364
01:21:16.704 --> 01:21:20.264
well as a RAF inhibitor or as trametinib, a MEK

1365
01:21:20.304 --> 01:21:20.704
inhibitor.

1366
01:21:23.024 --> 01:21:26.464
So one question that you may ask is, "Okay, this is a nice regulatory

1367
01:21:26.524 --> 01:21:30.384
interaction. I'm buying the biophysics, but is it going to

1368
01:21:30.444 --> 01:21:34.004
be enough? Does it going to have enough juice to just stabilize that

1369
01:21:34.044 --> 01:21:37.944
interaction in the case where you have upregulation of the MAP

1370
01:21:37.984 --> 01:21:41.464
kinase cascade in cancer?" You have massive upregulation,

1371
01:21:41.564 --> 01:21:45.444
massive growth of cells through this pathway, complex

1372
01:21:45.564 --> 01:21:49.384
feedback loops. And this is hard even for

1373
01:21:49.424 --> 01:21:52.124
really potent inhibitors like trametinib to be effective.

1374
01:21:52.884 --> 01:21:56.504
So we thought about where else is the MAP kinase pathway important

1375
01:21:56.904 --> 01:21:59.954
in disease biology, and one area is in

1376
01:21:59.964 --> 01:22:03.924
RASopathies. Most common RASopathy is Noonan syndrome.

1377
01:22:03.944 --> 01:22:07.804
These are developmental disorders where the RAS pathway or the

1378
01:22:07.824 --> 01:22:10.504
MAP kinase pathway is slightly upregulated.

1379
01:22:11.324 --> 01:22:14.284
So there's a growth advantage to certain cells during development.

1380
01:22:14.904 --> 01:22:17.064
They lead to a set of different

1381
01:22:18.324 --> 01:22:20.924
issues during organ development, depending on the

1382
01:22:20.944 --> 01:22:23.944
RASopathy. But the point

1383
01:22:23.984 --> 01:22:27.724
biochemically is that we have a slight upregulation of this pathway.

1384
01:22:27.804 --> 01:22:31.604
So rather than a tsunami, like we have in cancer, we just have a little too

1385
01:22:31.644 --> 01:22:34.464
much. We need a better dam to hold back that pathway.

1386
01:22:34.964 --> 01:22:38.454
So we reasoned that if we stabilize this

1387
01:22:38.484 --> 01:22:42.264
interaction, this is really the bottom of the pathway.

1388
01:22:42.444 --> 01:22:45.584
All of the mutations in Noonan syndrome, there are 10 different proteins that are

1389
01:22:45.624 --> 01:22:49.504
mutated in Noonan syndrome, that we're capturing this flux at

1390
01:22:49.544 --> 01:22:53.224
the bottom of the pathway. So since we're at the bottom of the pathway, all of the

1391
01:22:53.264 --> 01:22:56.124
mutations should be treatable with this approach.

1392
01:22:56.784 --> 01:22:59.434
And you can see there are several different proteins, probably some of your

1393
01:22:59.444 --> 01:23:03.434
favorite MAP kinase proteins. 50% of the mutations are in

1394
01:23:03.504 --> 01:23:07.424
SHP2 to upregulate the pathway, and 8% are in CRAF

1395
01:23:07.484 --> 01:23:07.984
itself.

1396
01:23:09.404 --> 01:23:11.834
So these mutations in CRAF, guess where they are?

1397
01:23:12.964 --> 01:23:16.944
You're right. They're at the binding site, a 259 binding site

1398
01:23:17.324 --> 01:23:20.864
of 1433. So this is a major regulatory node for

1399
01:23:20.924 --> 01:23:24.604
CRAF, and therefore, to get over this regulation and upregulate the

1400
01:23:24.644 --> 01:23:25.844
pathway, the

1401
01:23:26.924 --> 01:23:28.804
proteins are mutated at this site.

1402
01:23:29.624 --> 01:23:31.824
And these disease mutations are all fairly rare.

1403
01:23:31.884 --> 01:23:34.524
This is the most common, and they're the most highly

1404
01:23:36.664 --> 01:23:40.044
correlated with cardiomyopathy, which you could argue is the worst

1405
01:23:41.104 --> 01:23:43.524
life-limiting effect of Noonan syndrome.

1406
01:23:44.364 --> 01:23:47.944
So we asked, okay, if you have mutations here,

1407
01:23:48.744 --> 01:23:51.024
why does that lead to pathway activity?

1408
01:23:51.454 --> 01:23:54.844
And it's a combination both of binding affinity, so we have a lower binding

1409
01:23:54.884 --> 01:23:58.564
affinity, and because of that lower binding affinity, there's

1410
01:23:58.624 --> 01:24:02.604
more dephosphorylation by SHOC2 kinase, less

1411
01:24:03.864 --> 01:24:06.814
phosphorylation, less protection by 1433.

1412
01:24:08.524 --> 01:24:12.324
So what that leads to is an inhibition of the protein-protein

1413
01:24:12.364 --> 01:24:15.314
interaction and an increase in the pathway activity.

1414
01:24:15.864 --> 01:24:19.824
So with our molecular glues that bind right here, we can pull that pathway

1415
01:24:19.844 --> 01:24:23.144
down back about as well. This is using phospho-ERK again.

1416
01:24:24.444 --> 01:24:27.764
SHOC2 mutations hyperactivate the phosphatase.

1417
01:24:28.144 --> 01:24:30.424
We can block that about as well as trametinib.

1418
01:24:30.844 --> 01:24:34.744
And then two mutations in CRAF itself, high pathway activity,

1419
01:24:35.164 --> 01:24:38.144
we can block it about as well again, as trametinib does.

1420
01:24:41.704 --> 01:24:45.544
So in short, our goal is to systematically identify protein-protein

1421
01:24:45.604 --> 01:24:46.884
interaction stabilizers,

1422
01:24:48.264 --> 01:24:50.124
stabilizing native protein complexes.

1423
01:24:50.504 --> 01:24:54.184
We can do this selectively because we're binding to a composite surface, and that

1424
01:24:54.224 --> 01:24:58.144
composite surface is unique or at least highly unusual, even

1425
01:24:58.184 --> 01:24:59.204
though the two proteins

1426
01:25:00.084 --> 01:25:01.564
may be very common proteins.

1427
01:25:02.504 --> 01:25:06.364
We're using this to modulate undruggable targets and mutated protein-protein

1428
01:25:06.404 --> 01:25:10.104
interactions, like inLike with Noonan

1429
01:25:10.164 --> 01:25:13.984
syndrome, and extending to new protein-protein interaction networks to

1430
01:25:14.124 --> 01:25:17.604
see what we've learned, how that can be translated to other networks.

